Project Treble
Introduction:
The Problem: The "Big Messy Tower"
Before 2017 (Android 8.0): updating an Android phone was like trying to replace the bottom floor of a skyscraper without the whole building collapsing.
The Old Way: The Android OS (the "house") and the Hardware Drivers (the "foundation") were tangled together.
The Result: To update the OS, manufacturers had to rewrite huge chunks of hardware code. This took months, leading to "Android Fragmentation."


The "Why" behind the Delay
"Why was it so slow? It wasn't because Google was lazy. It was because the Architecture was a 'Monolithic Blob.'
Before 2017, if you wanted to update the Android OS (the software), you had to manually stitch it into the Silicon (the hardware drivers). As our partners told us, updating a device was 'incredibly time-consuming and costly.
The Android OS Framework developed by Google,
The Vendor Implementation (drivers, HALs, low-level libraries) provided by OEMs,
The Applications built by third parties.
Historically, this coupling made OS updates slow and costly, as device makers had to re-integrate and test the entire software stack for each update.

"It was like having to rebuild your entire car engine just because you wanted to change the radio software."
What is PROJECT TREBLE
Project Treble separates the Android OS Framework from the vendor hardware code implementations

With Project Treble, Google is introducing a “vendor interface“, which will work similarly to the Compatibility Test Suite (CTS).

The CTS makes sure the app developers don’t have to custom design their apps for different manufacturers and different hardware.

In the case of Android updates, Vendor Test Suite (VTS) will cut off the work required by the silicon manufacturers, thus speeding up the update.
HOW Android Updates work After Oreo 
It’s important to reiterate that Android uses the Linux kernel under the hood.  A kernel is the part of an operating system which handles input/output and computer instructions from the application layer, essentially allowing the application software to communicate with the hardware.
To make changes to the way Android handles this communication is to make some notable changes to the way the Linux kernel operates.
To solve the hardware abstraction layer issue, Android 8.0 Oreo and later version like Android 9.0 Pie formalize the division between hardware subsystems like audio or camera, and their clients on the software side. These new formal divisions specify the interface between a HAL and its users.
The goal of a HIDL is to allow the framework to be replaced without having to rebuild HALs. HALs will be built by vendors or SoC makers and put in a /vendor partition on the device, enabling the framework,
in its own partition, to be replaced with an over-the-air update (OTA) without recompiling the HALs. To update devices running earlier versions of Android to Android O, developers can wrap both conventional and legacy HALs in a new HIDL interface too.
